## 5. Layer 3A — Physical Quantity Acquisition Interface

### What this layer does
Converts raw sensor data into the four physical input quantities required by the Physical Layer.

### V — Dynamic Spatio-temporal Envelope
```
Input:   current velocity, acceleration, defensive driving safety margin
Output:  3D safety envelope dimensions
Source:  onboard motion sensors (IMU, wheel odometry)
```

### θ — Surface Normal Angle
```
Input:   LiDAR point cloud
Output:  surface normal angle per spatial direction
Method:  point cloud normal estimation (mature, library-ready)
```

### μ — Friction Coefficient
```
Input:   terrain texture analysis + contact history
Output:  friction coefficient estimate with confidence interval
Method:  terrain classification (existing solutions reusable)
Note:    accuracy degrades in extreme weather — confidence tagging required
```

### R — Medium Resistance
```
Input:   FMCW LiDAR continuous wave backscatter signal
Output:  medium continuity normalized value
Method:  backscatter intensity discontinuity detection
Key:     TMF's specific reinterpretation of FMCW output —
         measures where traversable medium ends,
         not what object caused it to end
```

---

## 6. Layer 3B — Semantic Acquisition Interface

### What this layer does
Converts scene perception results into structured semantic inputs for the Semantic Layer.

### Traffic Rule Input
```
Source:  HD map + real-time signal recognition
Format:  structured rule tags (LLM pre-processing compatible)
```

### Scene Understanding Input
```
Source:  camera + LLM reasoning
Output:  semantic scene labels
         - pedestrian position and intent
         - vehicle trajectory prediction
         - special zone recognition (school, hospital, construction)
```

### Risk Source Point Input — Radius-Jump Method
```
Source:  LiDAR radial distance discontinuity detection
Output:  set of risk source point coordinates on traversable medium boundary
Use:     elevates semantic layer attention weight at potential emergence loci
         (occlusion corners, parked vehicle edges, building recesses)
Note:    same signal used in existing literature for negative obstacle detection;
         TMF reinterprets it as a prior over imminent actor emergence risk
```

